{
  "texts": [
    "We, thus, now briefly explain, and our explanation will wrap up by drawing once again upon the three-door Monty Hall Problem = MHP 3, now familiar to our readers given earlier discussion of this problem.",
    "To explain, let us first consider the function of arguments: Arguments are often instruments of persuasion.",
    "In fact, an argument's persuasiveness may be of greater import than its veracity or validity, depending on the arguer's intent with regard to its audience.",
    "Logicist AI has largely followed in the footsteps of formal logic by privileging the dialectic (i.e., in a word, logic) over the other members of the ancient trivium.",
    "By eschewing rhetoric (essentially argumentation as treated today what is known as informal logic; see Groarke, 1996 Groarke, /2017)), most logicist AI fails to appreciate the persuasive function of argument and its role in dialogical games such as disputation."
  ]
}